			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2018</a> paper:</span><br><i>Deriving fluent internal domain-specific languages from grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ArvidButting.html">Arvid Butting</a>, <a href="../profile/ManuelaDalibor.html">Manuela Dalibor</a>, <a href="../profile/GerritLeonhardt.html">Gerrit Leonhardt</a>, <a href="../profile/BernhardRumpe.html">Bernhard Rumpe</a>, <a href="../profile/AndreasWortmann.html">Andreas Wortmann</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3276604.3276621">10.1145/3276604.3276621</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The paper mainly targets domain-specific languages or modeling languages, including their design or use.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It includes substantial tool support or infrastructure relevant for engineering/using languages.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> It relies on formal methods (definitions/proofs/semantic properties) beyond informal description.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> It uses compilation/generation/refinement to derive executable artifacts (vertical transformations).
</li></ul></li></ul>
